1.Simple HTML Program to Display a Heading
Here’s a simple HTML program that displays the heading “HTML defines the content and structure of your website” on the web browser:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>HTML defines the content and structure of your website</h1>
</body>
</html>

2. Purpose of Comments in HTML
Purpose of Comments in HTML:

Documentation: Comments can be used to explain and document the HTML code, making it easier for others (or yourself) to understand the code later.
Code Organization: Comments can help organize code by dividing it into sections and providing descriptions.
Debugging: Comments can be used to temporarily disable code for debugging purposes.
Example of Using Comments in HTML:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML Comments Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <!-- This is a comment. It will not be displayed in the browser. -->
    <h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
    <!-- The following paragraph describes the purpose of the website -->
    <p>This is a sample paragraph to demonstrate HTML comments.</p>
</body>
</html>

3. HTML Program with Heading, Paragraph, Horizontal Line, and Line Break
Here’s an HTML program that includes a heading, a paragraph, a horizontal line, and a line break:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple Layout</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to My Simple Web Page</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph of text that provides some information about the page.</p>
    <hr> <!-- Horizontal line -->
    <p>Here is another paragraph after a horizontal line.</p>
    <br> <!-- Line break -->
    <p>This paragraph is separated by a line break from the previous one.</p>
</body>
</html>


