4. Tags and Elements in HTML
Tag:

A tag is a fundamental building block of HTML. It is used to define elements within an HTML document.
Tags are enclosed in angle brackets (< >).
Element:

An element includes the opening tag, content, and the closing tag. For example, <p>This is a paragraph.</p>.
Example:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML Tags and Elements</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>HTML Tags and Elements</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph element.</p> <!-- This is a comment -->
    <a href="https://www.example.com">This is a link.</a>
</body>
</html>

5. What is the DOCTYPE Declaration in HTML?
Definition:

The <!DOCTYPE html> declaration is used to specify the HTML version and ensure that the browser renders the page in standards mode.
It helps the browser to interpret and display the HTML document correctly.
Purpose:

Standards Compliance: It ensures that the browser uses the latest standards to render the HTML document.
Compatibility: Helps prevent rendering issues by specifying the HTML version.
Example:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>DOCTYPE Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Example of DOCTYPE Declaration</h1>
</body>
</html>
